          "body": "Numbers 16 casts a long shadow in the New Testament and in Hebrews' argument for the unique priesthood of Christ. Jude 11 cites 'the rebellion of Korah' as the third in a triad of apostolic warnings (alongside Cain's way and Balaam's error) — Korah's sin being the rejection of divinely-appointed mediation in favor of self-appointed access to God. Hebrews 5:1-5 argues that the high priest must be 'called by God, just as Aaron was' — the precise category Numbers 16 establishes by fire and by swallowing earth. Aaron's act in 16:46-48 is a type of Christ's high-priestly mediation: an authorized priest, bearing atoning offering, standing in the space between divine wrath and human death, turning back the plague by atonement. Where Aaron ran with a censer, Christ entered the holy place with His own blood (Hebrews 9:12, 24-26), making atonement once for all. And where Korah was swallowed alive into Sheol for unauthorized approach, Christ descended to the place of death by divine appointment and rose, opening access to the Father for all who come through Him rather than around Him."
